First, let's find the symmetric difference AΔB. The symmetric difference of two sets is the set of elements which are in either of the sets but not in their intersection. 

A = {1, 2, 3}
B = {2, 3, 4}

Intersection of A and B, A∩B = {2, 3}

AΔB = (A - A∩B) ∪ (B - A∩B) = ({1} ∪ {4}) = {1, 4}

Now, let's find the complement of AΔB, denoted as (AΔB)'.

Since we are not given a universal set, we will assume the universal set U contains all the elements in sets A and B. 

U = {1, 2, 3, 4}

(AΔB)' = U - AΔB = {1, 2, 3, 4} - {1, 4} = {2, 3}

Now, we need to find the symmetric difference of (AΔB)' and A, denoted as ((AΔB)'ΔA).

(AΔB)' = {2, 3}
A = {1, 2, 3}

Intersection of (AΔB)' and A, ((AΔB)'∩A) = {2, 3}

((AΔB)'ΔA) = ((AΔB)' - ((AΔB)'∩A)) ∪ (A - ((AΔB)'∩A)) = ({ } ∪ {1}) = {1}

So, the result of (AΔB)'ΔA is {1}.
